Introduction:¶

The dataset we will be working with comes from a two-year historical log that corresponds to the years 2011 and 2012 from the Capital Bikeshare System in Washington D.C. This data is publicly available at http://capitalbikeshare.com/system-data. There are two different datasets, one measured by day and one measured by hour. We will be working with the dataset measured by hour.¶
This dataset contains information related to the number of bike rentals over the course of time. It also includes information about the time of year and the weather during which these rentals took place. The total number of rentals is further divided into two categories: registered rentals and casual rentals. There are a total of 17 columns and 17,379 rows in this set.¶
We can also see that this data does not contain any missing values. In terms of real-world value, it seems logical that we would want to find ways to maximize our bike rentals. One way to do this is to look at the timepoints where sales are the highest and lowest. A second way is to take a closer look at how various weather conditions affect the rental sales. These two factors, timepoints and weather conditions, will be the focus of our analysis.¶

In [137]:
def biplot(score,coeff,labels=None):
    xs = score[:,0]
    ys = score[:,1]
    n = coeff.shape[0]
    scalex = 1.0/(xs.max() - xs.min())
    scaley = 1.0/(ys.max() - ys.min())
    plt.scatter(xs * scalex,ys * scaley,s=5, c = hours.weathersit, alpha = 0.8, cmap = 'Greens', label = '1')
    plt.colorbar(label = 'Weather(Light = Clear, Dark = Severe)')
    plt.title('PCA Biplot: Rental Numbers based on Weather')
    for i in range(n):
        plt.arrow(0, 0, coeff[i,0], coeff[i,1],color = 'blue',alpha = 0.5)
        if labels is None:
            plt.text(coeff[i,0]* 1.15, coeff[i,1] * 1.15, "Var"+str(i+1), color = 'blue', ha = 'center', va = 'center', fontsize = 15)
        else:
            plt.text(coeff[i,0]* 1.15, coeff[i,1] * 1.15, labels[i], color = 'blue', ha = 'center', va = 'center', fontsize = 15)
 
    plt.xlabel("PC{}".format(1))
    plt.ylabel("PC{}".format(2))
    plt.grid()
    
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
biplot(xpca, np.transpose(pca.components_), list(hours_X))

We can see a few things from this biplot. First of all, we have colored our datapoints by weather conditions, where the lighter colored points mean clear weather. In contrast, the darker colored points indicate worse weather conditions. One relationship we can visualize here is that the number of bike rentals appears to be inversely related to the level of humidity. To take it a step further, it appears that the humidity has a larger effect on registered bike rentals than it does on casual rentals. In addition, if we look at the colors, we can see that the majority of dark-colored points, indicating bad weather, appear to be in the opposite direction of our rental vectors. This indicates that weather is likely a factor in determining the number of rentals.¶
By creating the correlation plot below, we can take a closer look at how the total, casual, and registered rentals correlate with humidity. As predicted, there is a stronger correlation with casual rentals than with registered rentals.¶

Supervised Analysis:¶

Although we set out to find relationships between weather and timepoints and the number of rentals, we found that working days and holidays had a high classification accuracy score. Therefore, we will investigate those variables further in our supervised analysis.¶
We will begin by using a k nearest neighbors classifier to predict whether it is a working day or not based on our rental numbers. We will then check the accuracy score of our model.¶
In [143]:
X = hours[['cnt', 'casual', 'registered']]
y = hours['workingday']

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=2)

m = model.fit(X, y)
y_pred = model.predict(X)

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
accuracy_score(y, y_pred)
Out[143]:
0.7659243915069912
For working days, our accuracy score with our supervised model is much higher than the score we achieved with our unsupervised model. Now, we will perform a cross validation score in order to use unseen data in our prediction. We will perform a 10-fold cross validation and then compute the mean score.¶
In [144]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
cv_score = cross_val_score(m, X, y, cv=10)
cv_score.mean()
Out[144]:
0.634388748771906
Our cross validation score is less than our accuracy score, but still above 60%. Now, let's see how our supervised model performs when we use our rental numbers to predict whether it is a holiday or not.¶

Conclusion:¶

We began our analysis by exploring the bike rentals dataset. During our exploration, we chose to focus on an area with potential to create value. We then created some exploratory plots in order to better visualize the relationships between the different variables within our data. We then took a closer look into these relationships by implementing both unsupervised and supervised classification methods. In the end, we found that some variables were better at predicting rentals than others.¶
Through our analysis, we saw that there were some correlations between humidity and the number of rentals. We also saw through various forms of machine learning that some of our best predictors were weather conditions, whether or not it was a holiday, and whether or not it was a working day. On the other hand, we noticed that other variables, such as the season, were not as strong at predicting our rental numbers.¶
We can draw some real world considerations from this analysis. First off, it appears that weather conditions have a stronger affect on rental numbers than the time of the year. This may present an opportunity to market rentals deeper into the off-seasons if the weather remains decent. Another consideration is that there are fewer overall casual rentals in comparison to registered rentals. In addition, the number of rentals do seem to fluctuate with the time of the day, as well as with holidays and working days. We may be able to use this information to our advantage in order to market and push casual rentals during times when registered rentals are at their lowest points, as there will be more bikes available for use.¶
